                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, April 8 (PTI): The government will bring an anti-torture law to ratify a UN convention against torture and other cruel and inhuman treatment or punishment .          
	The Union cabinet today approved a proposal to introduce the Prevention of Torture Bill, 2010 in Parliament,information and broadcasting minister Ambika Soni said. The convention was adopted by the UN General Assembly on December 9, 1975. India had signed it in 1997.                   
	 Melbourne (PTI): India and Australia have signed an education deal under which they have agreed to set up a joint education council and extend exchanges in the field of education. The deal was signed by human resource development minister Kapil Sibal and Australian deputy Prime Minister Julia Gillard in Melbourne.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): A handicapped woman, who had moved Bombay High Court against actor Salman Khan accusing him of exploiting her photograph, withdrew her petition after the court said it was inclined to dismiss it. The court, however, gave Phoolbanoo Bakshi Ilahi the liberty to file a complaint before a magistrate for damages. She has claimed that Salman had clicked a picture with her last year. She had asked Salman not to sell the photograph but she saw it in a newspaper later.                  
	 Ghaziabad (PTI): Sixteen girls of a government school in a Ghaziabad village have lodged a complaint against their English teacher, accusing him of molesting them. Krishna Avtar Tyagi, 55, also used to pass lewd comments on them, the girls said.                  
	 Behrampore: A clerk of a Kendriya Vidyalaya in Balurghat was killed along with the driver and an assistant of the car he was travelling in after it collided head-on with a truck on NH-34 in Murshidabads Beldanga in the early hours of Thursday. Swapan Banerjee, 50, was returning to his South Calcutta home from Balurghat with his wife Tuhina and son Satyaki when the accident occurred. Villagers took Tuhina and Satyaki to hospital.
                                                                                                                                              
